Meet Julie Newman

School/Position: Dartmouth High School - Math Teacher

Hometown: Dartmouth, Ma

Education: Dartmouth High School, University of Massachusetts Dartmouth

One goal I have achieved in my career so far that I feel most satisfied about: Building relationships with disengaged students by establishing trust and offering them a safe learning environment.

A long term goal I am working toward: Earning my Master’s Degree in Secondary Education

If I could travel anywhere in the world it would be: I would revisit Paris, France

Pet Peeve: People who always look for the negative in situations as opposed to a solution

Favorite leisure time activity: Refinishing old furniture

Favorite movie genre: Comedy

I think the world’s greatest invention is: The Dishwasher

My favorite motto or saying: “Ya get what ya get, and ya don’t get upset.”

What I like best about working at DPS: I am looking forward to working at DPS and becoming part of what I know is such a close knit community.

post_text: Moving new chrome books to Middle School for distribution next Wednesday and Thursday. These have all been enrolled, updated and inventoried - ready to go! Thanks to our proactive steps to go 1 to 1 and continue to upgrade our technology resources we are able to ensure our students are ready for this year no matter the educational model being used. Thanks to Chief Technology Officer Jonathan Gallishaw for his leadership in this department. And of course he will give credit to our tech dept: the folks on the ground making sure everything is working. There are no words to describe the countless hours our team has put in for the past 5 or 6 months in an effort to provide educational services. We can say the same about the funding it has taken to make this happen. Keeping it real and keeping it positive! Onward and upward!

post_text:
Important NEWS! This morning USDA Sec. Sonny Perdue released an announcement that All Breakfast and Lunch meals for school children will be FREE starting the first day of school through December 31, 2020!

This will have a substantial and positive impact on the nutrition and health for our students, at the same time, offer relief for families experiencing financial uncertainties. FREE meals at school provide a much needed convenience for busy families, too! As a result of this change, we will receive vital financial support for operating school nutrition programs across our country.

We invite ALL students to choose tasty meals when at school or from our Meals TO GO! More information will be sent out over the next weeks regarding our new meal ordering system.

Hello Parents/Guardians,

Our return to school survey closes tomorrow, Friday June 1oth at 5:00

Your input is important to us as we plan for a successful re-opening in September 2020. Please take a few minutes to complete this survey. This survey should take less than ten minutes. In addition to the multiple choice questions, there are periodic opportunities to provide additional comments. We respectfully request that you submit a survey response for EACH child separately.

The health, safety, and well-being of our students and staff remain our top priority. All decisions will be made based on current guidelines from public health officials and what is best for our community.

Thank you for taking the time to complete this survey and your ongoing support. The survey will close on Friday, July 10th at 5:00. Once again, please respond, we feel your input is important to our planning.

"Math in the Morning With Ms. Suzy!" Register your child for a 30-minute practice full of key principles for grades preK-5. Ms. Suzy will teach math and literacy concepts through movement! We are offering these lessons for free!

Math & Movement uses multi-sensory learning approaches to teach students valuable skills to succeed in their school’s math and reading curricula. Math & Movement recognizes that students learn through different styles which is why our exercises include teaching with visual, auditory, and kinesthetic elements aligned with most state standards. Dartmouth Parents' 14.0 in partnership with Real Life Princesses of Dartmouth and DNRT as well as our middle school and high school volunteers are presenting Enchanted Woods on July 11th from 9:30-1:30. We are capping the numbers so we ensure that each of our attendees has a magical experience- lots of time to see our characters, complete their scavenger hunt and explore the magical decorations while safely social distancing. Please sign up early so you don't miss your chance! We are asking that families who attend donate $5- $10 to DNRT to assist in their efforts to preserve Dartmouth's Trails. Love our trails!

Please note- we are still inviting MS and HS volunteers to dress as pirates, fairies, superheroes and princesses. DNRT will grant service hours to our special character volunteers AND you will be bringing joy to the littlest members of our Dartmouth Community- such a fun way to spend a morning! Please email Mary Waite, maryewaite@gmail.com, if your teen would like to volunteer. Sign ups are below.

HOTLINE NUMBERS

Here’s a list of hotlines that may help you in whatever situation you find yourself in.

Feeling Overwhelmed? If you don’t know where to start, we suggest dialing 2-1-1 on your phone to be connected with the national human service call center.

Massachusetts Information and Referral Hotline 2-1-1 (Connects callers to information about critical health and human services available in their community)

Contact Crisis Text Line by texting HOME to 741741(National crisis text line can connect to a trained counselor about any type of crisis)

Contact the Massachusetts Emergency Services Program/Mobile Crisis Intervention (ESP/MCI) - 1-877-382-1609

Massachusetts Child-at-Risk hotline at 800-792-5200

National Domestic Violence Hotline 1-800-985-5990 or Text TalkWithUs to 66746

Massachusetts residents can visit www.Buoy.com/mass to get advice from an online health assistant safely at home, for free. (COVID-19)

post_text:
We read some great tips this week on the Boston Mamas blog for families that are feeling overwhelmed. Here are a few of our favorites. Visit the blog to see the rest!

LOWER YOUR EXPECTATIONS. NOW LOWER THEM SOME MORE.
If a lot of structure works well for your family, then do that. If imposing a lot of structure is going to cause a lot of blow ups in your household right now… skip it. Do. What. Works.

REPEAT AFTER ME: THIS. IS. TEMPORARY.
No, we don’t know how long it will last. Yes, it’s hard to know what day it is. But it’s temporary. It is helpful to remind ourselves that during moments of feeling overwhelmed.

THANK YOU. PLEASE. I’M SORRY
Gratitude buoys our resilience. We are all experiencing moments of grief, irritability, or frustration. Saying the words to the people we live and interact with helps.
